Preheat your oven to 200°C. Pour a good glug of @oil{a good glug} onto a #baking tray{} and pop in your oven. Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil on high heat with @salt{0.5%tsp}. Peel the @potatoes{900%g}, chop them into 4cm chunks. Add the potatoes to the boiling water and cook until the edges have softened when you poke them with a knife, ~{7-8%minutes}.

While the potatoes cook, trim the tops from the @chantenay carrots{1} and halve lengthways. Pop them on a large baking tray and drizzle with @oil{a good glug}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, @ground cumin{1%tsp} and @sugar{1%tsp}. Toss to coat the carrots in the oil and spices and spread in a single layer at one end of the #baking tray{}. Carefully remove the @lamb roasting joint{450%g} from the netting (discard the netting). Rub the @harissa paste{1} (use less if you don't like heat) onto the lamb and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Place it on the other end of the carrot tray.

Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{}, pop back into the saucepan and sprinkle on half the @plain flour{24%g}. Give your pan a shake to fluff up the potato. Take your hot baking tray out of your oven, carefully transfer your potatoes onto it in a single layer, turning in the oil. Season with @salt{}. Roast the potatoes on the top shelf of your oven for ~{45-50%minutes}, turning halfway through.

Once the potatoes have been cooking for ~{10%minutes}, roast the lamb and carrots on the middle shelf of the oven for ~{25-30%minutes} for medium rare. Add an extra ~{5%minutes} if you like your lamb more cooked. Rest wrapped loosely in #foil{} for at least ~{10%minutes} before slicing. Pop the @cauliflower florets{1}(single layer) on a smallish baking tray or #ovenproof dish{}(in a single layer). Drizzle with @oil{a good glug} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Add the cauli to the bottom shelf of the oven to roast for the last ~{25%minutes} of potatoes' cooking time.

Meanwhile, heat a glug of @oil{a glug} in a saucepan over medium heat, stir in the remaining flour and cook for ~{1%minute}- you've made a roux! Gradually stir in the @water for the gravy{400%ml} and @chicken stock powder{1%tsp}, bring to the boil, stirring out any lumps that may form. Once boiling, lower the heat and simmer until the gravy has thickened to your liking, ~{15-20%minutes}. Meanwhile, grate the @mature cheddar cheese{1} and pop in a #bowl{}. Add the @dukkah mix{1} to the cheese and mix together.

In the last ~{5%minutes} of cauliflower cooking time, sprinkle over the cheese and dukkah and pop on the middle shelf for the last ~{5%minutes}. The lamb and carrots should be out of the oven now.

Once everything is cooked, thinly slice the lamb and serve with the carrots, potatoes and cheesy cauli. Add the lamb resting juices to the gravy if you want to make it a bit thinner. Drizzle the gravy over the meat and enjoy!